  <body>
    <h1>Japanese Egg Salad Sandwich (Tamago Sando)</h1>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <em>Japanese Egg Salad Sandwich (Tamago Sando)</em>
  </body>
 </html>

<img class="universal-image__image lazyloaded" src="https://imagesvc.meredithcorp.io/v3/mm/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fimages.media-allrecipes.com%2Fuserphotos%2F9144725.jpg&amp;w=160&amp;q=60&amp;c=sc&amp;poi=auto&amp;orient=true&amp;h=90" width="210" height="100" alt="" role="" data-expand="0" data-src="https://imagesvc.meredithcorp.io/v3/mm/image?url=https%3A%2F%2Fimages.media-allrecipes.com%2Fuserphotos%2F9144725.jpg&amp;w=160&amp;q=60&amp;c=sc&amp;poi=auto&amp;orient=true&amp;h=90">

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <p> Two things make this famous Japanese egg salad sando exceptional.</p>
<p>For one, the soft, buttery, slightly sweet Japanese milk bread is perfection with egg salad. And also, the super-savory Kewpie-style mayonnaise really makes the salad amazing. Chef John will show you "how to make a version of a mayonnaise so incredible, it literally has a cult following." </p>
  </body>   
 </html>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Ingredients</h1>
    
<ul>
    <li>4 large eggs</li>
</ul>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>For the Kewpie-Style Mayonnaise:</h1>
    <ul>

<li>½ cup mayonnaise

<li>¼ teaspoon kosher salt

<li>¾ teaspoon white sugar

<li>1 teaspoon Dijon mustard

<li>3 dashes hot sauce, or to taste

<li>1 teaspoon freshly squeezed lemon juice

<li>2 teaspoons rice vinegar
</ul>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>For the Sando:</h1>

<ul>
<li>½ teaspoon kosher
 <li>salt, or to taste

<li>¼ teaspoon white sugar

<li>1 pinch cayenne pepper

<li>1 tablespoon heavy cream

<li>4 slices soft white bread

<li>1 tablespoon unsalted butter, softened
</ul>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h1>Directions</h1>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h3>Step 1</h3> 
  </body>
 </html>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
   Place eggs in the bottom of a saucepan. Add 1/4 inch of water. Heat over medium-high heat and bring to a boil. Cover and steam for 11 minutes. Turn off the heat and drain water carefully; pour cold water over and let cool.
  </body>
 </html>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h3>Step 2</h3> 
  </body>
 </html>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
   Mix mayonnaise, salt, sugar, mustard, hot sauce, lemon juice, and vinegar for Kewpie-style mayonnaise together. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate until needed.
  </body>
 </html>

 <html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h3>Step 3</h3> 
  </body>
 </html>

<html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
  Peel eggs. Mash in a shallow bowl with the side and back of a fork until desired texture is reached. Add salt, sugar, cayenne, heavy cream, and 3 tablespoons Kewpie-style mayonnaise. Stir to combine. Wrap and refrigerate until well chilled, at least 1 hour. Taste and adjust seasonings.
  </body>
 </html>

 <html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h3>Step 4</h3> 
  </body>
 </html>

 <html>
  <head>
  </head>
  <body>
  Butter bread slices and use 1/2 of the egg salad on each sandwich. Cut crusts off before serving if you're fancy.
  </body>
 </html>